Also, we should here gather that he was at once condemned without trial, as is also stated by Dio (58. 1, 3); but it would appear from Pliny (N. H. 8. 40, 61, 145) that an execution, and therefore probably an examination, of his slaves took place. The words of Pliny, ‘cum animadvertere- tur ex causa Neronis Germanici fili in Titium Sabinum et servitia eius,’ show that these proceedings, though correctly dated by him, are mixed up in his mind with the charges against Nero in the following year (cp. 5. 3, 2). It is pos- sible that Nero may have been now impli- cated by name (see below, 57), or that the treason· of Sabinus may have been brought up again next year and laid to his charge.
